<para id="import-auto-id1830656">The measured data of <emphasis effect="italics">g</emphasis><sub>2</sub>(<emphasis effect="italics">τ</emphasis>) could be fitted with the parameters of <emphasis effect="italics">k</emphasis><emphasis effect="italics">m</emphasis> using the relationship of <link target-id="simpleaddmaaaaathml"/>, where <m:math><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mover accent="true"><m:mi>Γ</m:mi><m:mo>¯</m:mo></m:mover></m:mrow><m:mrow/></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0"> size 12{ {overline  {Γ}} } {}</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math> (<emphasis effect="italics">k</emphasis><sub>1</sub>), <emphasis effect="italics">k</emphasis><sub>2</sub>, and <emphasis effect="italics"> k</emphasis><sub>3</sub> describes the average, variance, and skewness (or asymmetry) of the decay rates of the distribution, and polydispersity index <m:math><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mi>γ</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">=</m:mo><m:mfrac><m:msub><m:mi>k</m:mi><m:mrow><m:mn>2</m:mn></m:mrow></m:msub><m:msup><m:mover accent="true"><m:mi>Γ</m:mi><m:mo>¯</m:mo></m:mover><m:mrow><m:mn>2</m:mn></m:mrow></m:msup></m:mfrac></m:mrow></m:mrow><m:mrow/></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0"> size 12{γ= {  {k rSub { size 8{2} } }  over  { {overline  {Γ}}  rSup { size 8{2} } } } } {}</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math> is used to indicate the width of the distribution. And parameters beyond <emphasis effect="italics">k</emphasis><sub>3</sub> are seldom used to prevent overfitting the data. Finally, the size distribution can be easily calculated from the decay rate distribution as described in <link target-id="import-auto-id1172762154266"/>. <link target-id="import-auto-id1172769802497"/> shows an example of data fitting using the cumulant method.</para>


